Then, the accretion is limited to the Eddinton rate,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{M}_{Edd}=\frac{4\pi G^{2}M_{BH}m_{p}}{\epsilon_{r}\sigma_{T}c},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{p}$
\end_inset

 is the proton mass, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{T}$
\end_inset

is the Thompson cross-section and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{r}$
\end_inset

is the radiative efficiency.
 The radiaitve efficiency is related to the radiated bolometric luminosity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{B}$
\end_inset

, and accretion rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{BH}$
\end_inset

, by
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\epsilon_{r}=\frac{L_{r}}{\dot{M}_{BH}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This simply gives the mass to energy conversion efficiency set by the amount
 of energy that can be extracted from the innermost stable orbit of an accretion
 disk around a black hole.
\end_layout

